Diamond Plots

Gjalt-Jorn Ygram Peters

2017-04-22 at 21:18:37

The examples are based on 201 participants.

Challenges when working with confidence intervals

The beliefs selected for this example are highDose_AttBeliefs_hallucinate, highDose_AttBeliefs_timeAwareness, highDose_AttBeliefs_memory, highDose_AttBeliefs_health, and highDose_AttBeliefs_better. The determinants with which the associations of these beliefs will be computed are highDose_attitude and highDose_intention.

Table 1: Correlation coefficients and their 95% confidence intervals for the associations between the beliefs and the direct measure of attitude, all regarding using a high dose of ecstasy.
  lower r upper
A high dose causes more hallucinations -.31 -.18 -.05
A high dose makes time pass faster -.16 -.02 .12
A high dose improves my memory .23 .35 .47
A high dose is better for my health .37 .48 .58
A high dose yields a better experience .58 .66 .73

For example, for the five beliefs related to using a high dose of ecstasy, the respective means are 5.44, 5.58, 2.85, 2.07, and 3.76, and their correlations with attitude are -.18, -.02, .35, .48, .66. This list of five values is quite straightforward to evaluate. However, when complemented with the lower and upper bounds of the confidence intervals, comparing these estimates requires evaluating fifteen values simultaneously, which carries a considerably higher load (see Table 1). For more associations, this number quickly increases. It would be useful if a method was available to facilitate interpretation of multiple confidence intervals simultaneously.

meanSDtoDiamondPlot(means = c(5.44, 5.58, 2.85, 2.07, 3.76),
                    sd = c(1.19, 1.42, 1.4, 1.14, 1.63),
                    ns = c(201, 201, 201, 201, 201),
                    labels = c('Hallucination',
                               'Time',
                               'Memory',
                               'Health',
                               'Experience'));
meanSDtoDiamondPlot(means = c(5.44, 5.58, 2.85, 2.07, 3.76),
                    sd = c(1.19, 1.42, 1.4, 1.14, 1.63),
                    ns = c(201, 201, 201, 201, 201),
                    labels = c('Hallucination',
                               'Time',
                               'Memory',
                               'Health',

  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(1, 7), breaks=1:7);
